//GOD1PRF:72937 But $\operatorname{Ker}(p) \subset \operatorname{Ker}(f)$ by hypothesis, and therefore $f^{\prime}$ is injective if and only if $\operatorname{Ker}(f)=\operatorname{Ker}(p)$.
