//GOD1PRF:915262 this set I contains 0 , and if it contains integers $r, s$ it clearly contains $r-s$; it is therefore a subgroup of the additive group $\mathbf{Z}$, and hence (§ 7, Example 8) there exists a unique integer $p \geqslant 0$ such that $\mathrm{I}=p \mathrm{Z}$. This integer $p$ is called the characteristic of the field K .
//GOD1PRF:915586 The characteristic $p$ of a field K may also be defined as follows: if the relation $r .1=0$ implies $r=0$, then $p=0$; if not, then $p$ is the smallest strictly positive integer such that $p .1=0$. In all cases, the relation $r .1=0$ means that $r$ is a multiple of $p$, or again : for $r .1$ to be non-zero it is necessary and sufficient that $r$ is not divisible by the characteristic of K .
//GOD1PRF:915982 It is important to observe that the characteristic of a field is always either 0 or a prime number. For suppose that the field K is of characteristic $p \neq 0$, and let $r, s$ be two integers such that
//GOD1PRF:916199 then we have
//GOD1PRF:916256 and since a field is an integral domain, it follows that either $r .1=0$ (in which case $p$ divides $r$ ) or $s .1=0$ (in which case $p$ divides $s$ ). This proves our assertion.
