//GOD1PRF:935136 Since the left-hand side of this relation is the set of all $y \in \mathrm{~K}$ for which there exist
//GOD1PRF:936133 particular, since $d \in(d)$, there exist $u_{1}, \ldots, u_{n} \in \mathrm{~K}$ such that
//GOD1PRF:936305 This result is sometimes called Bézout's theorem.\\
//GOD1PRF:936358 We have called $d$ a highest common factor of $x_{1}, \ldots, x_{n}$. This terminology is justified by the following result: for an element of K to divide each of $x_{1}, \ldots, x_{n}$, it is necessary and sufficient that it should divide $d$.
//GOD1PRF:936604 For the relation (1) shows that the ideal (d) contains each $x_{i}$, so that each $x_{i}$ is a multiple of $d$, and therefore every divisor of $d$ divides the $x_{i}$. Conversely, let $m \in \mathrm{~K}$ be a divisor of $x_{1}, \ldots, x_{n}$, say
//GOD1PRF:936995 so that $m$ divides $d$, and the proof is complete.\\
Admitted.

//GOD1:937835 coprime_family : "the family #6 indexed by #5 is coprime" | $\operatorname{hcf}(#6_i)=1$
Definition coprime_family :
  set -> (set -> set -> set) -> (set -> set -> set) ->
  set -> (set -> set) -> prop :=
  fun K add mul I x =>
    highest_common_factor K add mul I x (ring_one K mul).

//GOD1:937835 coprime_elements : "#4 and #5 are coprime in the ring #1" | $\operatorname{hcf}(#4,#5)=1$
Definition coprime_elements :
  set -> (set -> set -> set) -> (set -> set -> set) ->
  set -> set -> prop :=
  fun K add mul x y =>
    coprime_family K add mul 2 (fun i => if i = 0 then x else y).

Theorem god1_s31_theorem1_coprime_characterizations :
  forall K, forall add mul:set -> set -> set,
  forall n :e omega, forall x :e K :^: n,
    principal_ideal_domain K add mul ->
    (coprime_family K add mul n (fun i => x i)
    <-> forall d :e K,
      (forall i :e n, ring_divides K mul d (x i)) -> ring_unit K add mul d)
    /\ ((forall d :e K,
      (forall i :e n, ring_divides K mul d (x i)) -> ring_unit K add mul d)
    <-> exists coeff :e K :^: n,
      module_finitely_supported_sum K add n
        (fun i => mul (coeff i) (x i)) = ring_one K mul)
    /\ ((exists coeff :e K :^: n,
      module_finitely_supported_sum K add n
        (fun i => mul (coeff i) (x i)) = ring_one K mul)
    <-> forall y :e K, exists coeff :e K :^: n,
      module_finitely_supported_sum K add n
        (fun i => mul (coeff i) (x i)) = y).
let K add mul.
let n.
assume hn.
let x.
assume hx hPID.
apply andI.
//GOD1PRF:937960 theorem 1. Let $x_{1}, \ldots, x_{n}$ be elements of a principal ideal domain K . Then the following properties are equivalent:\\
//GOD1PRF:938452 Condition $a$ ) means that
//GOD1PRF:938536 whence $a$ ) and $d$ ) are equivalent. If the $x_{i}$ are coprime, then their common divisors are\\
//GOD1PRF:938636 the divisors of 1 , i.e., the units of K ; conversely, if every common divisor of the $x_{i}$ is a unit, then the (or, more correctly, a) h.c.f. of the $x_{i}$ is a unit, and since the multiples of a unit fill up the whole ring K we have $\left(x_{1}, \ldots, x_{n}\right)=\mathrm{K}$, so that $a$ ) and $b$ ) are equivalent. Finally, $a$ ) implies $c$ ) by Bézout's theorem ; and $c$ ) implies $d$ ), because $c$ ) means that the ideal ( $x_{1}, \ldots, x_{n}$ ) contains 1 and is therefore the whole of $K$.\\
Admitted.

Theorem god1_s31_theorem2_euclid_coprime_divisor_lemma :
